<doc id="1229368" wikidata="Q2298831" url="?curid=1229368" title="Asymmetric relation">
<text>In mathematics, an asymmetric relation is a binary relation formula_1 on a set formula_2 where for all formula_3 if formula_4 is related to formula_5 then formula_5 is &quot;not&quot; related to formula_7

== Formal definition ==

=== Preliminaries ===
A binary relation on formula_2 is any subset formula_1 of formula_10 Given formula_3 write formula_12 if and only if formula_13 which means that formula_12 is shorthand for formula_15 The expression formula_12 is read as &quot;formula_4 is related to formula_5 by formula_19&quot;

=== Definition ===

The binary relation formula_1 is called if for all formula_3 if formula_12 is true then formula_23 is false; that is, if formula_24 then formula_25 
This can be written in the notation of first-order logic as
formula_26
A logically equivalent definition is:
:for all formula_3 at least one of formula_12 and formula_23 is ,
which in first-order logic can be written as:
formula_30
A relation is asymmetric if and only if it is both antisymmetric and irreflexive, so this may also be taken as a definition.

== Examples ==

An example of an asymmetric relation is the &quot;less than&quot; relation formula_31 between real numbers: if formula_32 then necessarily formula_33 is not less than formula_34 More generally, any strict partial order is an asymmetric relation. Not all asymmetric relations are strict partial orders. An example of an asymmetric non-transitive, even antitransitive relation is the relation: if formula_2 beats formula_36 then formula_37 does not beat formula_38 and if formula_2 beats formula_37 and formula_37 beats formula_42 then formula_2 does not beat formula_44

Restrictions and converses of asymmetric relations are also asymmetric. For example, the restriction of formula_31 from the reals to the integers is still asymmetric, and the converse or dual formula_46 of formula_31 is also asymmetric.

An asymmetric relation need not have the connex property. For example, the strict subset relation formula_48 is asymmetric, and neither of the sets formula_49 and formula_50 is a strict subset of the other. A relation is connex if and only if its complement is asymmetric.

A non-example is the &quot;less than or equal&quot; relation formula_51. This is not asymmetric, because reversing for example, formula_52 produces formula_52 and both are true. The less-than-or-equal relation is an example of a relation that is neither symmetric nor asymmetric, showing that asymmetry is not the same thing as &quot;not symmetric&quot;.

The empty relation is the only relation that is (vacuously) both symmetric and asymmetric.

== Properties ==

The following conditions are sufficient for a relation formula_1 to be asymmetric:
* formula_1 is irreflexive and anti-symmetric (this is also necessary)
* formula_1 is irreflexive and transitive. A transitive relation is asymmetric if and only if it is irreflexive: if formula_57 and formula_58 transitivity gives formula_59 contradicting irreflexivity. Such a relation is a strict partial order.
* formula_1 is irreflexive and satisfies semiorder property 1 (there do not exist two mutually incomparable two-point linear orders)
* formula_1 is anti-transitive and anti-symmetric
* formula_1 is anti-transitive and transitive
* formula_1 is anti-transitive and satisfies semi-order property 1

== See also ==

* Tarski&#x27;s axiomatization of the reals – part of this is the requirement that formula_31 over the real numbers be asymmetric.

